       "category": "tips",
       "content": "Diligence is the easiest of the 4Ds to skip. The draft reads cleanly, the deadline is sticky, and you send. The cost shows up later when a partner flags a number that does not match your records or a colleague asks where a recommendation came from. Anthropic's own prompt engineering guidance points at a fix. The documented practice for outputs that involve reasoning: ask Claude to walk through its thinking step by step before delivering a conclusion. That trace lets you spot the moves the model made, surface the assumptions baked into the draft, and verify the claims that matter.\n\nThe tactical move on a Tuesday morning is small. Before you treat any Claude output as ready to send, run one follow-up prompt: \"Walk me through the choices you made in this draft. For each factual claim, tell me whether it came from the context I gave you, from your training data, or from a judgment call you made. Quote the source passage when applicable.\" Claude returns a short audit of its own output. The audit becomes the trace for Week 6 with no extra work. You spot the claims you most need to verify. You see the places where the model filled a gap that should have been filled by your knowledge of the partner, the program, or the specific number.\n\nThis is Diligence as a workflow. The model produces the draft. You produce the verification step. The chat history becomes your audit log and the artifact your team brings to Friday's discussion.",
